lood and soil." These speeches, often interpreted as key documents in the rise of modern nationalism, also contain Fichte's most sustained reflections on pedagogical issues, including his ideas for a new egalitarian system of Prussian national education. The contributors' reconsideration of the speeches deal not only with technical philosophical issues such as the relationship between language and identity, and the tensions between universal and particular motifs in the text, but also with issues of broader concern, including education, nationalism, and the connection between morality and politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEducation and statezGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 0aNational characteristics, GermanxHistoryy19th century. 4aCultural Studies : German Culture. 4aHistory : History. 4aPhilosophy : German Idealism. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Psychology. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aBreazeale, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreazeale, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBykova, Marina F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrowe, Benjamin D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarr, Arnold L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGottlieb, Gabriel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKinlaw, C. Jeffery, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerovich, Anthony N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRockmore, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRockmore, Tom, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchäfer, Rainer, econtributor.4ctb